Use `#if` preprocessor directives combined with the standard `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection` registration in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`** are predefined compilation constants in MAUI projects — no extra setup needed.
- Place each platform implementation under `Platforms/<platform>/` so it only compiles for that target (the default `.csproj` already scopes those folders).
- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere in shared code — the DI container resolves the right implementation per platform.
- If a platform has no implementation, registration is simply skipped. Guard against this with a fallback or a runtime check if needed.
